PREFACE.
THE Trustees of the University of Pennsylvania have long had
inliemplation to cause a Catalogue of their Library to be made,
with a view of increaseing it, and rendering it worthy of the first lite
rary institution of this commonwealth; but they were discouraged
not only by the small number of volumes that it contains, but by the
little attention that was paid to it for a considerable time, in conse
quence of the successive changes which the University experienced
in its organization, which occasioned the loss of many books, so
that the sets of valuable works have been broken, which it will be
necessary to replace entirely. The institution, however, having
made important changes in their internal arrangement, and having
determined to erect new building, in place of the former inconve
nient edifice, which building, it is expected, will be finished at the
close of the present year, it has been thought expedient to prepare
and published the present Catalogue of the few books at present pos
sessed by the University, among which, however, it will be found,
that there are a number of valuable works, and the whole, taken to-

gether, may be considered as a good nu meus for an academical
library
This liberty was begun by private denations of the friends of the
institution, among whom the Rev. William Smith, the first Provost
of the College and Academy, and Dr. McDowell, one of his succes-
sors, deserve to be particularly noticed. During the revolutionary
war, our little collection was enriched by a donation in books from
his majesty Louis the Sixteenth. These books, printed at the royal
twinting office, consist chiefly of mathematical works, of works on
natural history, among which is a collection of M. Buffons, and
some of the wattine historians. They have been all carefully
preserved, and will, it is hoped, long remain, a Memorial of the
liberality of that great and unfortunate Monarch. For a few years
past, the Board of Trustees havenernally kppropriated a sum of
money for the purchase of books, by means of which this liberty is
now suadually increaseing, and it is to be hoped, will continue to in
crease. But the fund of the University being limited, it is greatly
to be wished that the friends of public instruction may Oontibute
their aid to the attainment of this important object. Donations of
keoks, therefore, will be thankfully received, and the deserous don
ors will entitle themselves to the gratitude of future deserations.
